Less if you consider than analog triggers can provide a great range of functionality, most obvious in racing games (analog triggers for brake/gas are the ONLY way to play racing games with a controller). The button placement...frankly I think the dual shock is overrated. dual shoulder buttons? no thanks. It was never a good idea, 6 face 2 shoulder are just the best, bar none.<br>
The analog sticks on the dual shock are teh suxx0r too. Crappy grip, and there is virtually no resistance, negating the analog usefulness. I always find it hard to push the stick halfway up, because it has the resistance of a piece of paper.<br>
And don't get me started on the Dpad. That is ALMOST the worst Dpad ever invented. It's improved over the PS1 version because that one had too much grip, making hadokens painful, but when you compare playing street fighter on a sony pad after playing on one with a full D pad it's quite obvious that the response just isn't there.<br>
The dreamcast D pad jutted out horribly and was quite painful for extended play, but its still way better than the ps2 one because you could always get the exact responsiveness you wanted.<br>
The worst pad is still the gamecube, because it's basically wortless thanks to being the size of a dime, but the best is easily the Saturn/Xbox S controller pad (it's essentially the same). It's a circle, with the cross on it, so you can easily tell what direction you're pushing, but rather than just parts of it being elevated as a button the entire circular pad is seperate.<br>
